\begin_layout Subsection
Vasicek portfolio loss distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to model the loss probability distribution of the underlying
 credit portfolio of our synthetic CDO.
 The Gaussian copula model emerged during the late 1990’s as the market
 standard for pricing portfolio credit derivatives.
 It was popularized by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-9"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-10"

\end_inset

, becoming the prevalent approach used by practitioners and academics throughout
 the past decade.
 This model was not new, but in fact a simplified form of earlier one-factor
 models proposed by Vasicek in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-12"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-3"

\end_inset

 and almost identical to the original CreditMetrics model introduced by
 Gupton in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-11"

\end_inset

.
 Its main breakthrough was the analogy established between techniques used
 in credit risk management of loan portfolios and portfolios of credit securitie
s in derivatives such as CDOs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our approach goes back to the foundations of the Gaussian copula model proposed
 earlier by Vasicek, which provides a closed-form solution for the loss
 probability distribution given a large number of issuers in the underlying
 credit portfolio.
 Vasicek's model is founded on the principles outlined by the Merton model
 of a firm's capital structure
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-8"

\end_inset

, which establishes that credit default happen when the value of a firm's
 assets falls below the contractual value of its debt obligations within
 a certain horizon.
 In Merton's model, the debtor's assets dynamics is assumed to follow the
 Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dA_{i}}{A_{i}}=\mu_{i}dt+\sigma_{i}dW_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where, for each debtor 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in a credit portfolio, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents the debtor's assets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are respectively the mean and standard deviation of changes in the debtor's
 assets, and 
\begin_inset Formula $dW_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a Brownian Motion.
 This gives the value of the assets at a horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log A_{i}(T)=\log A_{i}(0)+(\mu_{i}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{i}^{2})T+\sigma_{i}\sqrt{T}z_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a standard normal variable.
 In this setup, the probability of a debtor to default on its obligations
 by a horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the probability of its assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 falling below its nominal debt obligations 
\begin_inset Formula $B{}_{i}$
\end_inset

, given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
p_{i} & =\textrm{P}\left[A_{i}(T)<B_{i}\right]\\
 & =\textrm{P}\left[z_{i}<\frac{\log\frac{B_{i}}{A_{i}(0)}-(\mu_{i}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{i}^{2})T}{\sigma_{i}\sqrt{T}}\right]\\
 & =\Phi\left[\frac{\log\frac{B_{i}}{A_{i}(0)}-(\mu_{i}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{i}^{2})T}{\sigma_{i}\sqrt{T}}\right]\\
 & =\Phi(z_{i}).
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is the cumulative standard normal distribution function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider a portfolio with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such debt obligations in equal nominal amounts, and let the probability
 of default of any debtor be 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=p$
\end_inset

.
 Also, allow for the random portion 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the assets of any two debtors to be correlated with correlation coefficient
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{i}=\Phi^{-1}(p)=y\sqrt{\rho}+\varepsilon_{i}\sqrt{1-\rho},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2},\ldots,\varepsilon_{i},\ldots\varepsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 are mutually independent and identically distributed standard normal variables.
 This is the well established one-factor modeling of portfolios where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as a common portfolio factor that emerges from a property
 of equicorrelated marginal normal distributions.
 In economic terms, the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 accounts for the systemic risk (e.g., wider economy) while the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 quantifies the specific risk of each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 From this we can derive the loss probability of obligor 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 conditional on the systemic factor 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\textrm{P}\left[\left.\varepsilon_{i}<\frac{\Phi^{-1}(p)-y\sqrt{\rho}}{\sqrt{1-\rho}}\right\vert y=Y\right]=\nonumber \\
\textrm{P}\left[\left.d_{i}=1\right\vert y=Y\right]\nonumber \\
\Rightarrow p(Y)=\Phi\left[\frac{\Phi^{-1}(p)-Y\sqrt{\rho}}{\sqrt{1-\rho}}\right],\label{eq:LGDi}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}=\boldsymbol{1}_{(A_{i}(T)<B_{i})}$
\end_inset

 as the unit step function to define a default indicator, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 in case of a default and zero otherwise.
 The total relative loss of the credit portfolio is then given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d=\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}d_{i},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}=1,
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}'\textrm{s}$
\end_inset

 represent the weights of the portfolio constituents.
 Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\textrm{E}\left[\left.d\right\vert Y\right]= & \sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}E\left[\left.d_{i}\right\vert Y\right]\\
= & \sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}\textrm{P}\left[\left.d_{i}=1\right\vert Y\right]\\
= & p(Y)\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}=p(Y),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\textrm{VAR}\left[\left.d\right\vert Y\right]= & \sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}^{2}\textrm{VAR}\left[\left.d_{i}\right\vert Y\right]\\
= & p(Y)\left[1-p(Y)\right]\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For very large portfolios, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}^{2}\Rightarrow\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\textrm{VAR}\left[\left.d\right\vert Y\right]=0,
\]

\end_inset

Thus, the cumulative probability function (CDF) of losses up to a proportion
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 of the total portfolio is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F(x)=\textrm{P}\left[d\leq x\right]\underset{{\scriptscriptstyle n\rightarrow\infty}}{\longrightarrow} & \textrm{P}\left[\textrm{E}\left[\left.d\right\vert Y\right]\leq x\right]=\\
 & \textrm{P}\left[p(Y)\leq x\right]=\\
 & \textrm{P}\left[Y\geq p^{-1}(x)\right]\Rightarrow
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(x)=\Phi\left[\frac{\sqrt{1-\rho}\Phi^{-1}(x)-\Phi^{-1}(p)}{\sqrt{\rho}}\right],\label{eq:CDF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the probability density function (PDF) from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-3"

\end_inset

 derived as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
f(x) & =\sqrt{\frac{1-\rho}{\rho}}\exp\left[-\frac{1}{2\rho}\Bigl(\sqrt{1-\rho}\Phi^{-1}(x)\right.\label{eq:PDF}\\
 & \left.-\Phi^{-1}(p)\Bigr)^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\Phi^{-1}(x)\right)^{2}\right].\nonumber 
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bootstrapping default probabilities from CDS spreads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to calibrate generic curves via the Vasicek portfolio loss distribution
s in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDS"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDF"

\end_inset

, we need to avail of default probabilities implied from market expectations.
 These default probabilities have a term structure and can be bootstrapped
 from market quotes of the CDS spreads.
 A CDS is a swap of cash for credit event protection where the protection
 buyer agrees to pay a regular fee (
\shape italic
spread
\shape default
) to the protection seller whom, in turn, is liable to pay the contractual
 value (
\shape italic
notional
\shape default
) to the protection buyer in case of a credit event
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since CDS contracts are standardized under the International Swaps and Derivativ
es Association (ISDA), the various definitions of credit events are available
 from the 2014 ISDA Credit Derivatives Definitions (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www2.isda.org/asset-classes/credit-derivatives/2014-isda-credit-derivatives
-definitions/
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that happens before the contractual expiration (
\shape italic
maturity
\shape default
) of the agreement.
 Note that the CDS acts as an insurance to the protection buyer against
 credit events (defaults), and even the fee paid is often called 
\shape italic
premium
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Financially, the CDS effectively has two legs, a premium and a protection
 leg.
 Mathematically, the premium leg of a CDS with notional 1 and maturity 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \textrm{Premium Leg PV}=\\
 & S_{j}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\left\{ (t_{n}-t_{n-1})\right.\\
 & \times\left.\left[(1-\alpha)B_{n}-\alpha B_{n-1}\right]\left[(1-\alpha)q_{n}-\alpha q_{n-1}\right]\right\} ,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 represents the premium payment dates in years from inception date 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and with maturity date 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{N}=T_{j}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the spread or premium agreed to be paid until credit event or maturity
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 is reached,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the discount factor computed from the risk-free rate on date 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the risk-neutral survival probability of the underlying credit by date
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the parameter that takes into account the accrued premium depending
 on the assumption of when default happens in the premium payment cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the payment frequency of a CDS is determined by the difference
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}-t_{n-1}$
\end_inset

, mostly quarterly for CDSs on developed markets currencies and semi-annually
 for emerging markets.
 Also, because this is a discrete representation of the CDS premium leg,
 a common assumption is that default happens in the middle of the premium
 payment period, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, the protection leg of the same CDS with notional 1 and and maturity
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Protection Leg PV}=(1-R)\sum_{n=1}^{m\cdot N}B_{n}\left[q_{n}-q_{n-1}\right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}$
\end_inset

 are defined as previously,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a annual frequency in we assume credit events may happen, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the recovery rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose 
\begin_inset Formula $m=12$
\end_inset

 (monthly discretization) for computational convenience, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"

\end_inset

 shows that the difference between daily discretization 
\begin_inset Formula $(m=365)$
\end_inset

 and monthly discretization 
\begin_inset Formula $(m=12)$
\end_inset

 produces an absolute error which is well within bid-ask spreads of market
 quotes.
 Also, we adopt a typical practitioner's assumption on the recovery rate,
 or 40% for senior unsecured debt and 20% for subordinated debt as supported
 by studies such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-4"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CDS spreads are quoted at par, i.e., the premium to be paid by protection
 buyers that would equalize the cash flows of the premium leg with the ones
 from the protection leg.
 This implies that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & S_{j}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\left\{ (t_{n}-t_{n-1})\left[(1-\alpha)B_{n}-\alpha B_{n-1}\right]\right.\nonumber \\
 & \left.\times\left[(1-\alpha)q_{n}-\alpha q_{n-1}\right]\right\} \nonumber \\
 & -(1-R)\sum_{n=1}^{m\cdot N}B_{n}\left[q_{n}-q_{n-1}\right]=0\label{eq:CDS}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only unknown that needs to be calculated from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDS"

\end_inset

 is the probability of survival term structure 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},q_{2},\ldots,q_{n},\ldots,q_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 To that end, we adopt the market practice presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-13"

\end_inset

 which uses a reduced-form (or intensity-based) model as the solution to
 the probability of survival term structure, or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{n}=e^{-h(t_{n})t_{n}}\label{eq:qn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a hazard rate stepwise function, basically a constant from one maturity
 date 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j-1}$
\end_inset

 to another 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 in the term structure.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDS"

\end_inset

 is applied recursively through all maturities 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1},T_{2},\ldots,T_{j},\ldots,T_{n_{j}}$
\end_inset

 in order to bootstrap 
\begin_inset Formula $h(T_{j})$
\end_inset

 for each maturity.
 This results in the term structure of survival probabilities that can then
 be calculated with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:qn"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This process applies for CDS quotes of one single issuer.
 In order to imply the representative term structure for a certain rating
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and maturity 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 with a number of issuers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

, we calculate the respective survival probability as the geometric mean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{kj}=\left(q_{kj}^{(1)}q_{kj}^{(2)}q_{kj}^{(3)}\ldots q_{kj}^{(i)}\ldots q_{kj}^{(n_{i})}\right)^{\frac{1}{n_{i}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Finally, the default probabilities can be calculated from survival probabilities
 as simply 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{kj}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calibration of generic credit curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now show the application of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDF"

\end_inset

 to generate credit spreads for different ratings and through the term-structure
 of survival probabilities as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:qn"

\end_inset

.
 Consider the tranche 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of the CDO defined by its detachment point 
\begin_inset Formula $ku_{j}$
\end_inset

 and attachment point 
\begin_inset Formula $(k-1)u_{j}$
\end_inset

 for maturity 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The cumulative expected loss of this tranche is defined by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textrm{E}_{k}\left[\textrm{Loss}_{j}\right]=\textrm{E}\left[\left((x-ku_{j})^{-}-(k-1)u_{j}\right)^{+}\right],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a random variable representing the losses in the portfolio, 
\begin_inset Formula $(A)^{-}=\min(A,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(A)^{+}=\max(A,0)$
\end_inset

.
 We can also express this expectation through 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDF"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \textrm{E}_{k}\left[\textrm{Loss}_{j}\right]=\\
 & u_{j}\left\{ k\Phi\left[\frac{\sqrt{1-\rho_{j}}\Phi^{-1}(ku_{j})-\Phi^{-1}(p_{j})}{\sqrt{\rho_{j}}}\right]\right.\\
 & \left.-(k-1)\Phi\left[\frac{\sqrt{1-\rho_{j}}\Phi^{-1}((k-1)u_{j})-\Phi^{-1}(p_{j})}{\sqrt{\rho_{j}}}\right]\right\} .
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the same expectation can be expressed through the survival
 probabilities bootstrapped from the CDS quotes of each respective rating
 and maturity.
 We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textrm{E}_{k}\left[\textrm{Loss}_{j}\right]=u_{j}(1-q_{kj}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{kj}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:qn"

\end_inset

 for maturity 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 and rating 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Combining these two results leads to the error function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \varepsilon_{k}(u_{j},\rho_{j},p_{j})=\\
 & u_{j}\left\{ k\Phi\left[\frac{\sqrt{1-\rho_{j}}\Phi^{-1}(ku_{j})-\Phi^{-1}(p_{j})}{\sqrt{\rho_{j}}}\right]\right.\\
 & -(k-1)\Phi\left[\frac{\sqrt{1-\rho_{j}}\Phi^{-1}((k-1)u_{j})-\Phi^{-1}(p_{j})}{\sqrt{\rho_{j}}}\right]\\
 & -(1-q_{kj})\Biggr\}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calibrating the loss distribution of our synthetic CDO means finding the
 values of the three unknowns 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{j},\rho_{j},p_{j})$
\end_inset

 that minimize the sum of the squares of this error function, i.e.,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min\sum_{k=1}^{n_{k}}\mathbf{1}_{k}\epsilon_{k}^{2}(u_{j},\rho_{j},p_{j}),
\]

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{1}_{k}=\begin{cases}
1 & \textrm{if }q_{kj}\textrm{ is available,}\\
0 & \textrm{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we have three parameters to be calibrated, we require at least three
 equations for the error functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{k}$
\end_inset

, i.e., at least three groups of issuer of a certain rating from which we
 were able to bootstrap survival probabilities such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n_{k}}\mathbf{1}_{k}\geq3$
\end_inset

.
 However, approximations may be used where this does not apply.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n_{k}}\mathbf{1}_{k}=2$
\end_inset

, we may fix the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j}$
\end_inset

 and then calibrate 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{j},p_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 Or in case 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n_{k}}\mathbf{1}_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, we may fix 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{j},\rho_{j})$
\end_inset

 and find 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Generic credit curves in different currencies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One fundamental premise of our approach lies on the fact that, in an ideal
 world, each issuer's default dynamics should be 
\shape italic
unique
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
independent
\shape default
 of the currency in which debt is denominated.
 The uniqueness argument suggests that each issuer possesses a unique probabilit
y of survival term structure from which debt and CDS spreads can be derived
 in any currency.
 This is not solid mathematically, given that survival probabilities are
 implied from currency denominations under different risk-neutral measures.
 However, this not a significant error in practice and an important assumption
 we adopted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On independence between the credit default and the foreign exchange (FX)
 dynamics, while this is reasonable during the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risk-on
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 portion of economic cycles, we acknowledge that default-FX independence
 is less realistic during 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risk-off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 periods.
 Perhaps this is the reason why 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

over 85% of the emerging market debt outstanding (in U.S.
 dollar terms) is denominated in developed market currencies
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-7"

\end_inset

.
 USD-denominated debt from emerging markets issuers is more attractive to
 market participants, and therefore more liquid, because it acts as a natural
 hedge against default-FX dependence.
 But we argue that this problem can be mitigated by hedging the FX exposure
 in the FX markets, as most of the the more sophisticated market participants
 do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, ignoring the mathematical rigor of measure theory, we assume the flexibili
ty of constructing credit spread term structures in any currency through
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDS"

\end_inset

, provided the term structure of the survival probabilities is given.
 For instance, if we are able to calibrate a survival probability term structure
 for USD-Senior Unsecured-Technology-BBB, we may now construct the complete
 generic credit curve for CHF-Senior Unsecured-Technology-BBB through 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CDS"

\end_inset

, where the only difference is that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the CHF discount factor.
 The same goes to bootstrapping the survival probabilities through CDS quotes
 of different currency denominations.
 We have in fact tested this assumption by comparing probabilities of survival
 for single issuers with CDS quotes in different currencies.
 Although not exactly the same as our assumption would determine, the difference
s found in the probabilities of survival for different maturities were negligibl
e.
\end_layout

